ly films and illuminating black urban life in this period, is the first detailed look at the numerous early relationships between African Americans and cinema. It investigates African American migrations onto the screen, into the audience, and behind the camera, showing that African American urban populations and cinema shaped each other in powerful ways. Focusing on Black film culture in Chicago during the silent era, Migrating to the Movies begins with the earliest cinematic representations of African Americans and concludes with the silent films of Oscar Micheaux and other early "race films" made for Black audiences, discussing some of the extraordinary ways in which African Americans staked their claim in cinema's development as an art and a cultural institution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in motion pictures. 0aAfrican Americans in the motion picture industry. 0aAfrican AmericansxMigrationsxHistoryx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxMigrationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCinémaxPublicsxÉtats-Unis. 0aMotion picture audiencesxUnited States. 0aMotion picture audienceszUnited States. 0aNoirs américains au cinéma. 0aNoirs américains dans l'industrie cinématographique. 0aNoirs américainsxMigrationsxHistoirex20e sièclexUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936409423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520936409.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-